\title{2nd Sunday of Advent 2025}
\tag{cmc}
\date{2025-12-07}
\author{liamoc}
\quote{
  Populus Sion, ecce Dóminus véniet ad salvándas gentes: et audítam fáciet Dóminus glóriam vocis suæ, in lætítia cordis vestri.}
\p{This was a big Sunday at [All Saints Ainslie](https://allsaintsainslie.org.au). In the morning a small group of us sang Bach's [Jesu, Joy of Man's Desiring](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T5Df7f_BLU8):}
\quote{
    \poem{
      \line{Jesu, joy of man's desiring,}
      \line{Holy wisdom, love most bright;}
      \line{Drawn by Thee, our souls aspiring}
      \line{Soar to uncreated light.\br}
        
      \line{Word of God, our flesh that fashioned,}
      \line{With the fire of life impassioned,}
      \line{Striving still to truth unknown,}
      \line{Soaring, dying round Thy throne.\br}
        
      \line{Through the way where hope is guiding,}
      \line{Hark, what peaceful music rings;}
      \line{Where the flock, in Thee confiding,}
      \line{Drink of joy from deathless springs.\br}
        
      \line{Theirs is beauty's fairest pleasure;}
      \line{Theirs is wisdom's holiest treasure.}
      \line{Thou dost ever lead Thine own}
      \line{In the love of joys unknown.}
    }
}
\p{But, more significantly, we had our annual Lessons and Carols service. I cantored for the initial [Matin Responsory](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9uJdSvo1e2U) based on a Nunc Dimittis by Palestrina (despite the fact the Carols for Choirs edition says it's based on a Magnificat):} 
\quote{\poem{\line{\strong{I look from afar,}}
\line{And lo, I see the power of God coming, and a cloud covering the whole Earth.}
\line{\strong{Go ye out to meet him and say:}}
\line{Tell us, art thou he that should come to reign over thy people Israel?}
\line{High and low, rich and poor, one with another,}
\line{Go ye out to meet him and say:}
\line{Hear, O thou Shepherd of Israel, thou that leadest Joseph like a sheep,}
\line{Tell us, art thou he that should come?}
\line{Stir up thy strength, O Lord, and come}
\line{To reign over thy people, Israel.}
\line{\strong{Glory be to the Father and to the Son, and to the Holy Ghost.}}
\line{I look from afar,}
\line{And lo, I see the power of God coming, and a cloud covering the whole Earth.}
\line{Go ye out to meet him and say:}
\line{Tell us, art thou he that should come to reign over thy people Israel?}}}

\p{ We had several guest singers join us including Rachel Mink and Dan Walker from Luminescence. Rachel sang the initial verse of [Once In Royal David's City](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rA4Ng96nb3Y), after which we processed to the remaining verses. After the first lesson from yours truly, we performed Ord's [Adam Lay Ybounden](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oykLGvCfGCI): }
\quote{\poem{\line{Adam lay ybounden, bounden in a bond.}
\line{Four thousand winter thought he not too long.}
\line{And all was for an apple, an apple that he took,}
\line{As clerkes finden written in their book.}
\line{Ne had the apple taken been, the apple taken been,}
\line{Ne had never our ladye a been heavené queen.}
\line{Blessed be the time that apple taken was,}
\line{Therefore we moun singen \em{Deo Gracias}.}}}
