\p{Then we processed out [while shepherds washed their socks](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZOA2Y9Ms34s) and ascended to the organ loft for the remainder of the service, where we performed Warlock's [Bethlehem Down](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gQnuxaqbYx8). I heard that anthem was written on a napkin by an alcoholic and antitheist Peter Warlock in exchange for beer money, and that he died a few years after writing it. But the anthem itself is quite special.}
\quote{\poem{\line{When He is King we will give him the King's gifts,}
  \line{Myrrh for its sweetness, and gold for a crown,}
  \line{"Beautiful robes", said the young girl to Joseph}
  \line{Fair with her first-born on Bethlehem Down.}
  \line{\br}
  \line{Bethlehem Down is full of the starlight}
  \line{Winds for the spices, and stars for the gold,}
  \line{Mary for sleep, and for lullaby music}
  \line{Songs of a shepherd by Bethlehem fold.}
  \line{\br}
  \line{When He is King they will clothe Him in grave-sheets,}
  \line{Myrrh for embalming, and wood for a crown,}
  \line{He that lies now in the white arms of Mary}
  \line{Sleeping so lightly on Bethlehem Down.}
  \line{\br}
  \line{Here He has peace and a short while for dreaming,}
  \line{Close-huddled oxen to keep Him from cold,}
  \line{Mary for love, and for lullaby music}
  \line{Songs of a shepherd by Bethlehem fold.}}}
\p{This was followed by another congregational carol with Willcocks descant, [Hark the Herald Angels Sing](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Bwn0k0k8xI) and our last anthem of the evening, Wood's [Hey you! The Middle Ball](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qf202pdjMZk). }
\quote{
  \poem{
    \line{O thou the central orb of righteous love,}
    \line{Pure beam of the Most High,}
    \line{Eternal Light of this our wintry world,}
    \line{Thy radiance bright awakes new joy in faith,}
    \line{Hope soars above.}
    \line{\br}
    \line{Come, quickly come and let thy glory shine,}
    \line{Gilding our darksome heav'n with rays divine.}
    \line{Thy saints with holy lustre round thee move,}
    \line{As stars about thy throne, set in the height}
    \line{Of God's ordaining counsel, }
    \line{As thy sight gives measured grace to each.}
    \line{Thy power to prove.}
    \line{\br}
    \line{Let thy bright beams disperse the gloom of sin,}
    \line{Our nature all shall feel eternal day,}
    \line{In fellowship with thee,}
    \line{Transforming day to souls erewhile unclean,}
    \line{now pure within.}
    \line{\br}
    \line{Amen.}
  }
}
\p{Of course, it wouldn't be a Christmas Carols service without the "Word of the Father" chord, so we finished up with Willcocks' arrangement of [O Come, All Ye Faithful](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RkS57yCIk7E).
}

